Creating streams.

Streams can come from many sources, but four of them cover almost everything you will do. The first, and by far the most common, is calling stream on a collection you already have. The second is stream dot of, which builds a stream from a literal sequence of values you list out. The third is a numeric range: int-stream dot range gives you a run of integers with the end excluded, and range-closed includes the end.

The fourth source is the infinite stream, and it comes in two forms. Stream dot iterate starts from a seed and applies a function repeatedly, so iterate from one, doubling each time, gives you one, two, four, eight, and so on. Stream dot generate calls a supplier over and over, which is handy for things like random numbers.

Here is the catch with those last two. They are infinite. They will happily produce values forever. So you must cap them with limit, giving a count, before you attach a terminal operation. If you forget the limit, the pipeline simply never ends. One more thing worth knowing: the primitive streams, int-stream, long-stream, and double-stream, both avoid boxing and hand you numeric helpers like sum and average directly.
